degree Celsius: The degree Celsius is the unit of temperature on the Celsius temperature scale, one of two temperature scales used in the International System of Units (SI), the other being the closely related Kelvin scale. The degree Celsius can refer to a specific point on the Celsius temperature scale or to a difference or range between two temperatures. It is named after the Swedish astronomer Anders Celsius (1701–1744), who proposed the first version of it in 1742. The unit was called centigrade in several languages for many years. In 1948, the International Committee for Weights and Measures renamed it to honor Celsius and also to remove confusion with the term for one hundredth of a gradian in some languages. Most countries use this scale.
degree Fahrenheit: The Fahrenheit scale is a temperature scale based on one proposed in 1724 by the physicist Daniel Gabriel Fahrenheit (1686–1736). It uses the degree Fahrenheit as the unit. Several accounts of how he originally defined his scale exist, but the original paper suggests the lower defining point, 0 °F, was established as the freezing temperature of a solution of brine made from a mixture of water, ice, and ammonium chloride. The other limit established was his best estimate of the average human body temperature, originally set at 90 °F, then 96 °F.

eBioscience: eBioscience is a biotechnology company that specializes in providing innovative tools and reagents for life science research, particularly in the fields of immunology, cell biology, and molecular biology.
example to be eventually removed: "Example to be eventually removed" refers to a sample or instance that is intended to be discarded or eliminated from consideration in future analyses or discussions.
failed exploratory term: A failed exploratory term is a concept or keyword that, when searched or analyzed, does not yield relevant or meaningful results in a specific biomedical context.
gram: The gram is a unit of mass in the International System of Units (SI) equal to one thousandth of a kilogram.
gram per deciliter: A gram per deciliter is a unit of measurement that expresses the concentration of a substance in a solution, indicating how many grams of that substance are present in one deciliter (one-tenth of a liter) of liquid.
gram per liter: A gram per liter is a unit of concentration that expresses the mass of a substance in grams contained in one liter of solution.
hertz: The hertz is the unit of frequency in the International System of Units (SI), often described as being equivalent to one event per second. The hertz is an SI derived unit whose formal expression in terms of SI base units is 1/s or s−1, meaning that one hertz is one per second or the reciprocal of one second. It is used only in the case of periodic events. It is named after Heinrich Rudolf Hertz (1857–1894), the first person to provide conclusive proof of the existence of electromagnetic waves. For high frequencies, the unit is commonly expressed in multiples: kilohertz (kHz), megahertz (MHz), gigahertz (GHz), terahertz (THz).
hour: An hour is a unit of time historically reckoned as 1⁄24 of a day and defined contemporarily as exactly 3,600 seconds (SI). There are 60 minutes in an hour, and 24 hours in a day.
kilogram: The kilogram is the base unit of mass in the International System of Units (SI), equal to one thousand grams. It has the unit symbol kg. The word "kilogram" is formed from the combination of the metric prefix kilo- and gram; it is colloquially shortened to "kilo".
left handed: In human biology, handedness is an individual's preferential use of one hand, known as the dominant hand, due to and causing it to be stronger, faster or more dextrous. The other hand, comparatively often the weaker, less dextrous or simply less subjectively preferred, is called the non-dominant hand. In a study from 1975 on 7,688 children in US grades 1–6, left handers comprised 9.6% of the sample, with 10.5% of male children and 8.7% of female children being left-handed. Overall, around 90% of people are right-handed. Handedness is often defined by one's writing hand. It is fairly common for people to prefer to do a particular task with a particular hand. Mixed-handed people change hand preference depending on the task.
liter: The litre or liter is a metric unit of volume. It is equal to 1 cubic decimetre (dm3), 1000 cubic centimetres (cm3) or 0.001 cubic metres (m3). A cubic decimetre occupies a volume of 10 cm × 10 cm × 10 cm and is thus equal to one-thousandth of a cubic metre.
mass percentage: Mass percentage is the ratio of the mass of a specific component in a mixture to the total mass of the mixture, expressed as a percentage.
mass volume percentage: Mass volume percentage is a concentration measurement that expresses the mass of a solute in grams per 100 milliliters of solution.
metadata complete: "Metadata complete" refers to the state in which all necessary descriptive information about a dataset is fully provided, ensuring clarity and context for its interpretation and use.
metadata incomplete: "Metadata incomplete" refers to a situation where essential information about a dataset or resource is missing, making it difficult to fully understand or utilize the data effectively.
meter: The metre is the base unit of length in the International System of Units (SI). Since 2019, the metre has been defined as the length of the path travelled by light in vacuum during a time interval of ⁠1/299792458⁠ of a second, where the second is defined by a hyperfine transition frequency of caesium.
microgram: In the metric system, a microgram or microgramme is a unit of mass equal to one millionth of a gram. The unit symbol is μg according to the International System of Units (SI); the recommended symbol in the United States and United Kingdom when communicating medical information is mcg. In μg, the prefix symbol for micro- is the Greek letter μ (mu).
microgram per liter: A microgram per liter is a unit of measurement that indicates the concentration of a substance, representing one millionth of a gram of that substance in one liter of liquid.
microliter: The litre or liter is a metric unit of volume. It is equal to 1 cubic decimetre (dm3), 1000 cubic centimetres (cm3) or 0.001 cubic metres (m3). A cubic decimetre occupies a volume of 10 cm × 10 cm × 10 cm and is thus equal to one-thousandth of a cubic metre.
microliters per minute: Microliters per minute is a unit of measurement that quantifies the flow rate of a liquid, indicating the volume in microliters that passes through a given point in one minute.
micrometer: Micrometer can mean:Micrometer (device), used for accurate measurements by means of a calibrated screw Micrometre, a millionth of a metre
micromolar: Molar concentration (also called amount-of-substance concentration or molarity) is the number of moles of solute per liter of solution. Specifically, It is a measure of the concentration of a chemical species, in particular, of a solute in a solution, in terms of amount of substance per unit volume of solution. In chemistry, the most commonly used unit for molarity is the number of moles per liter, having the unit symbol mol/L or mol/dm3 (1000 mol/m3) in SI units. Molar concentration is often depicted with square brackets around the substance of interest; for example with the hydronium ion [H3O+] = 4.57 x 10-9 mol/L.
micromole: The mole (symbol mol) is a unit of measurement, the base unit in the International System of Units (SI) for amount of substance, an SI base quantity proportional to the number of elementary entities of a substance. One mole is an aggregate of exactly 6.02214076×1023 elementary entities (approximately 602 sextillion or 602 billion times a trillion), which can be atoms, molecules, ions, ion pairs, or other particles. The number of particles in a mole is the Avogadro number (symbol N0) and the numerical value of the Avogadro constant (symbol NA) expressed in mol−1. The relationship between the mole, Avogadro number, and Avogadro constant can be expressed in the following equation:The current SI value of the mole is based on the historical definition of the mole as the amount of substance that corresponds to the number of atoms in 12 grams of 12C, which made the molar mass of a compound in grams per mole, numerically equal to the average molecular mass or formula mass of the compound expressed in daltons. With the 2019 revision of the SI, the numerical equivalence is now only approximate, but may still be assumed with high accuracy.
milligram: The kilogram is the base unit of mass in the International System of Units (SI), equal to one thousand grams. It has the unit symbol kg. The word "kilogram" is formed from the combination of the metric prefix kilo- and gram; it is colloquially shortened to "kilo".
milligram per milliliter: A milligram per milliliter is a unit of concentration that expresses the mass of a substance in milligrams contained in one milliliter of solution.

milliliter per liter: A milliliter per liter is a unit of measurement that expresses the volume of a substance in milliliters contained in one liter of solution.
millimeter: The millimetre or millimeter is a unit of length in the International System of Units (SI), equal to one thousandth of a metre, which is the SI base unit of length. Therefore, there are one thousand millimetres in a metre, and there are ten millimetres in a centimetre.

minute: A minute is a unit of time defined as equal to 60 seconds. It is not a unit in the International System of Units (SI), but is accepted for use with SI. The SI symbol for minutes is min. The prime symbol ′ is also sometimes used informally to denote minutes.
molar: Molar may refer to:Molar (tooth), a kind of tooth found in mammals Molar (grape), another name for the Spanish wine grape Listan Negro Molar (unit), a unit of concentration equal to 1 mole per litre Molar quantities, such as molar mass, molar volume, etc. El Molar, Tarragona, a village in the comarca (county) of Priorat, province of Tarragona in the autonomous region of Catalonia, Spain El Molar, Madrid, a town in the north of the Community of Madrid in the road to Burgos, after San Agustín de Guadalix
month: A month is a unit of time, used with calendars, that is approximately as long as a natural phase cycle of the Moon; the words month and Moon are cognates. The traditional concept of months arose with the cycle of Moon phases; such lunar months ("lunations") are synodic months and last approximately 29.53 days, making for roughly 12.37 such months in one Earth year. From excavated tally sticks, researchers have deduced that people counted days in relation to the Moon's phases as early as the Paleolithic age. Synodic months, based on the Moon's orbital period with respect to the Earth–Sun line, are still the basis of many calendars today and are used to divide the year.
named class expression: A named class expression is a specific category in biomedical classification that is defined by a unique name and encompasses a set of related entities or concepts.
nanogram: A nanogram is one billionth of a gram, commonly used to measure very small quantities of substances in biomedical contexts.
nanoliter: The litre or liter is a metric unit of volume. It is equal to 1 cubic decimetre (dm3), 1000 cubic centimetres (cm3) or 0.001 cubic metres (m3). A cubic decimetre occupies a volume of 10 cm × 10 cm × 10 cm and is thus equal to one-thousandth of a cubic metre.
nanometer: The nanometre, or nanometer, is a unit of length in the International System of Units (SI), equal to one billionth or one thousand million of a meter (0.000000001 m) and to 1000 picometres. One nanometre can be expressed in scientific notation as 1 × 10−9 m and as ⁠1/1000000000⁠ m.

With the 2019 revision of the SI, the numerical equivalence is now only approximate, but may still be assumed with high accuracy.
organizational term: An organizational term is a label used to categorize and describe a specific concept or entity within a structured framework in the biomedical field.
out of scope: In project management, scope is the defined features and functions of a product, or the scope of work needed to finish a project. Scope involves getting information required to start a project, including the features the product needs to meet its stakeholders' requirements.
pM1 (colon): pM1 (colon) refers to the presence of distant metastases in the colon cancer staging system, indicating that cancer cells have spread to distant organs or tissues.
pM1 (kidney): pM1 (kidney) refers to the presence of distant metastases in the kidney, indicating that cancer has spread from its original site to this organ.
pM1 (lung): pM1 (lung) refers to the presence of distant metastases in the lungs from a primary tumor, indicating advanced cancer spread beyond the original site.
pM1 (ovary): pM1 (ovary) refers to the presence of metastatic cancer cells in the ovaries, indicating that the cancer has spread beyond its original site to this specific location.
pM1a (colon): pM1a (colon) refers to a classification of colon cancer where there is evidence of distant metastasis to one or more regional lymph nodes.
pM1a (lung): pM1a (lung) refers to the presence of distant metastasis in the lung tissue from a primary tumor, indicating advanced-stage cancer.
pM1b (colon): pM1b (colon) refers to a classification of colon cancer where there is distant metastasis to one or more non-regional lymph nodes.
pM1b (lung): pM1b (lung) refers to the presence of distant metastases in the lungs from a primary tumor, indicating advanced cancer spread beyond the original site.
pN0 (colon): pN0 (colon) indicates that there is no regional lymph node involvement in colon cancer, meaning no cancer cells are detected in the nearby lymph nodes.
pN0 (kidney): pN0 (kidney) indicates that there is no regional lymph node involvement in the staging of kidney cancer.
pN0 (lung): pN0 (lung) indicates that there is no regional lymph node involvement detected in a patient with lung cancer.
pN0 (ovary): pN0 (ovary) indicates that there is no regional lymph node involvement in ovarian cancer, meaning that cancer has not spread to nearby lymph nodes.
pN1 (colon): pN1 (colon) refers to the pathological classification indicating that cancer has spread to one to three regional lymph nodes in the colon.
pN1 (kidney): pN1 (kidney) refers to the presence of cancerous lymph nodes in the regional area surrounding the kidney, indicating a spread of kidney cancer beyond the primary tumor site.
pN1 (lung): pN1 (lung) refers to the pathological classification indicating that cancer has spread to nearby lymph nodes in the lung region but not to more distant sites.
pN1 (ovary): pN1 (ovary) refers to the presence of regional lymph node metastasis in ovarian cancer, indicating that cancer cells have spread to nearby lymph nodes.
pN1a (colon): pN1a (colon) refers to the presence of cancerous lymph nodes in the regional area, specifically indicating that one to three nearby lymph nodes are affected by metastasis in colon cancer.
pN1b (colon): pN1b (colon) refers to the pathological classification indicating that cancer has spread to one to three regional lymph nodes, specifically in the pericolic or perirectal areas, without distant metastasis.
pN1c (colon): pN1c (colon) refers to the presence of cancerous lymph nodes in the vicinity of the colon, indicating that the cancer has spread to nearby lymph nodes but not to distant sites.
pN2 (colon): pN2 (colon) refers to the pathological classification indicating that cancer has spread to two or more regional lymph nodes in the colon.
pN2 (lung): pN2 (lung) refers to the classification of regional lymph node involvement in lung cancer, indicating that cancer has spread to multiple lymph nodes on the same side of the chest as the primary tumor.
pN2a (colon): pN2a (colon) refers to the pathological classification indicating that cancer has spread to 4 to 6 regional lymph nodes in the colon.
pN2b (colon): pN2b (colon) refers to a classification of colorectal cancer where cancer has spread to multiple regional lymph nodes, specifically affecting four or more nodes in the mesenteric or pericolic areas.
pN3 (lung): pN3 (lung) refers to the classification of regional lymph node involvement in lung cancer, indicating that cancer has spread to multiple lymph nodes on the same side of the chest or to lymph nodes in the supraclavicular region.
pT0 (colon): pT0 (colon) indicates that there is no evidence of primary tumor in the colon, suggesting that the cancer has not invaded the colon tissue.
pT0 (kidney): pT0 (kidney) indicates the absence of detectable primary tumor in the kidney, suggesting that there is no evidence of cancer in that organ.
pT0 (lung): pT0 (lung) indicates the absence of primary tumor tissue in the lung, suggesting that no tumor is detectable at the site.
pT0 (ovary): pT0 (ovary) indicates that there is no evidence of primary tumor in the ovary, suggesting that the ovarian tissue appears normal or unaffected by cancer.
pT1 (colon): pT1 (colon) refers to a classification of colon cancer where the tumor has invaded the submucosa but has not penetrated deeper layers of the colon wall.
pT1 (kidney): pT1 (kidney) refers to a classification of kidney cancer where the tumor is confined to the kidney and measures 7 centimeters or less in greatest dimension.
pT1 (lung): pT1 (lung) refers to a classification of lung cancer where the tumor is 3 centimeters or smaller and is confined to the lung without invasion into nearby structures.
pT1 (ovary): pT1 (ovary) refers to a classification indicating that a tumor in the ovary is confined to the organ itself and has not spread beyond it.
pT1a (kidney): pT1a (kidney) refers to a classification of kidney cancer where the tumor is 7 centimeters or smaller and is confined to the kidney without any spread to nearby tissues or lymph nodes.
pT1a (lung): pT1a (lung) refers to a classification of lung cancer where the tumor is 3 centimeters or smaller in greatest dimension and is confined to the lung without invasion into surrounding structures.
pT1a (ovary): pT1a (ovary) refers to a classification of ovarian cancer indicating that the tumor is confined to one ovary and is either not visible or only microscopically detectable.
pT1b (kidney): pT1b (kidney) refers to a classification of kidney cancer where the tumor is 2 to 7 centimeters in greatest dimension and is confined to the kidney without any spread to nearby lymph nodes or distant sites.
pT1b (lung): pT1b (lung) refers to a classification of lung cancer where the tumor is 3 to 4 centimeters in greatest dimension and is confined to the lung without invasion of nearby structures.
pT1b (ovary): pT1b (ovary) refers to a classification of ovarian cancer indicating that the tumor is invasive and has spread to one or both ovaries but is confined to the ovaries without involvement of other pelvic structures.
pT1c (ovary): pT1c (ovary) refers to a classification of ovarian cancer where the tumor is confined to one or both ovaries but has spread to other pelvic tissues or has malignant cells in ascites or peritoneal washings.
pT2 (colon): pT2 (colon) refers to a classification in cancer staging indicating that the tumor has invaded the muscularis propria layer of the colon but has not penetrated through the serosa or into adjacent structures.
pT2 (kidney): pT2 (kidney) refers to a classification indicating that a kidney tumor has invaded the renal capsule or perinephric fat but has not spread to nearby lymph nodes or distant sites.
pT2 (lung): pT2 (lung) refers to a classification in lung cancer staging indicating a tumor that is larger than 3 cm but not larger than 5 cm, and may involve the main bronchus or the visceral pleura, but does not invade the chest wall or diaphragm.
pT2 (ovary): pT2 (ovary) refers to a classification indicating that ovarian cancer has spread to one or both ovaries and involves the surrounding tissues but has not spread to the pelvic wall or abdominal cavity.
pT2a (kidney): pT2a (kidney) refers to a classification of kidney cancer where the tumor is larger than 7 centimeters but not extending beyond the kidney capsule.
pT2a (lung): pT2a (lung) refers to a classification of lung cancer where the tumor is larger than 3 cm but not larger than 5 cm and may involve the main bronchus or the visceral pleura, without any invasion into the chest wall or diaphragm.
pT2a (ovary): pT2a (ovary) refers to a classification indicating that ovarian cancer has spread to one or both ovaries and involves the pelvic tissues but not beyond the pelvic cavity.
pT2b (kidney): pT2b (kidney) refers to a classification of kidney cancer where the tumor is larger than 7 centimeters and has not spread beyond the kidney.
pT2b (lung): pT2b (lung) refers to a classification of lung cancer where the tumor is larger than 3 cm but not larger than 5 cm and may invade nearby structures or the pleura, indicating a specific stage of tumor progression.
pT2b (ovary): pT2b (ovary) refers to a classification indicating that ovarian cancer has spread to one or both fallopian tubes and/or the pelvic peritoneum, but not beyond the pelvis.
pT2c (ovary): pT2c (ovary) refers to a classification indicating that ovarian cancer has spread to both ovaries and possibly to nearby pelvic tissues, but not to distant sites.
pT3 (colon): pT3 (colon) refers to a classification indicating that a colon tumor has invaded through the muscularis propria into the subserosa or into nearby tissues but has not spread to distant sites or lymph nodes.
pT3 (kidney): pT3 (kidney) refers to a classification of kidney cancer where the tumor has grown into surrounding tissues or structures but has not spread to distant sites.
pT3 (lung): pT3 (lung) refers to a classification of lung cancer where the tumor has invaded nearby structures, such as the chest wall or diaphragm, but has not spread to distant sites.
pT3 (ovary): pT3 (ovary) refers to a classification of ovarian cancer where the tumor has spread beyond the ovaries to the peritoneum or other pelvic structures but not to distant sites.
pT3a (kidney): pT3a (kidney) refers to a classification of kidney cancer where the tumor has invaded the perinephric fat but is not extending beyond Gerota's fascia.
pT3a (ovary): pT3a (ovary) refers to a classification of ovarian cancer where the tumor has spread beyond the ovaries to the peritoneum but not to other organs, indicating a more advanced stage of the disease.
pT3b (kidney): pT3b (kidney) refers to a classification of kidney cancer where the tumor has invaded the renal vein or its branches but has not spread to distant sites.
pT3b (ovary): pT3b (ovary) refers to a classification of ovarian cancer where the tumor has spread to the peritoneum outside the pelvis but not to distant organs, indicating advanced local disease.
pT3c (kidney): pT3c (kidney) refers to a classification of kidney cancer where the tumor has invaded the renal vein or its branches but has not spread to distant sites.
pT3c (ovary): pT3c (ovary) refers to a classification of ovarian cancer indicating that the tumor has spread to the peritoneum and/or has metastasized to the lymph nodes, with extensive tumor involvement.
pT4 (kidney): pT4 (kidney) refers to a classification of kidney cancer indicating that the tumor has grown beyond the kidney and surrounding tissues into nearby structures or organs.
pT4 (lung): pT4 (lung) refers to a classification in lung cancer staging indicating that the tumor has invaded nearby structures, such as the chest wall, diaphragm, or mediastinum, or has caused other significant local effects.
pT4a (colon): pT4a (colon) refers to a classification of colon cancer where the tumor has penetrated through the visceral peritoneum but does not involve other organs or structures.
pT4b (colon): pT4b (colon) refers to a classification in colorectal cancer staging indicating that the tumor has penetrated through the visceral peritoneum and has metastasized to other organs or structures within the abdominal cavity.
pTis (colon): pTis (colon) refers to a stage of colon cancer where there is a presence of carcinoma in situ, indicating that cancerous cells are found in the innermost layer of the colon but have not invaded deeper tissues or spread to other parts of the body.
pTis (lung): pTis (lung) refers to a stage of lung cancer where there is the presence of carcinoma in situ, indicating abnormal cells that have not invaded surrounding tissues.
pending final vetting: "Pending final vetting" refers to the status of a process or item that is awaiting thorough review and approval before it can be officially accepted or implemented.

placeholder removed: "Placeholder removed" refers to the process of eliminating a temporary or substitute element that was used to fill a space or represent something until the final item or information is available.
ready for release: "Ready for release" refers to a state in which a biological product, such as a drug or vaccine, has completed all necessary testing and quality control measures, confirming its safety, efficacy, and compliance with regulatory standards for distribution and use.
requires discussion: "Requires discussion" refers to a situation or topic that needs further conversation or deliberation to clarify, resolve, or understand its complexities.

second: The second is a unit of time derived from the division of the day first into 24 hours, then to 60 minutes, and finally to 60 seconds each. tar: Tar is a dark brown or black viscous liquid of hydrocarbons and free carbon, obtained from a wide variety of organic materials through destructive distillation. Tar can be produced from coal, wood, petroleum, or peat.
term imported: "Term imported" refers to a concept or term that has been brought into a specific context or database from an external source for use in classification or description.
term split: A term split refers to the division of a single medical term into two or more distinct terms to clarify meaning or improve specificity in communication.
terms merged: "Terms merged" refers to the process of combining two or more related concepts or terms into a single, unified term to streamline classification or improve clarity in biomedical terminology.
to be replaced with external ontology te: "To be replaced with external ontology term" means substituting a specific term with a standardized term from an external classification system to ensure consistency and clarity in communication.
universal: Universal is the adjective for universe.
volume percentage: Volume percentage is a measure of concentration that expresses the volume of a solute as a percentage of the total volume of the solution.
week: A week is a unit of time equal to seven days. It is the standard time period used for short cycles of days in most parts of the world. The days are often used to indicate common work days and rest days, as well as days of worship. Weeks are often mapped against yearly calendars. There are just over 52 weeks in a year. The term "week" may also be used to refer to a sub-section of the week, such as the workweek and weekend.
year: A year is a unit of time based on how long it takes the Earth to orbit the Sun. In scientific use, the tropical year and the sidereal year are more exact. The modern calendar year, as reckoned according to the Gregorian calendar, approximates the tropical year by using a system of leap years.
zip: Zip, Zips or ZIP may refer to:
